<p></p>.<p>
Mastitis is an inflammation of the breast tissue, most often caused by an infection. Mastitis is most common in lactating women. Symptoms include a hard, firm area in the breast that is usually painful. Other symptoms include</p>.<p>
<a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/pain_quiz/quiz.htm" rel="quiz" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">Pain</a> while <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/breastfeeding/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">breastfeeding</a>, <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/aches_pain_fever/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">fever</a>, <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/chills/symptoms.htm" rel="sym" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">chills</a>, and generally feeling unwell (malaise 
or <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/fatigue/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">fatigue</a>) can be other symptoms of mastitis. Sometimes, blood or pus can be seen in <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/breastfeeding/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">breast milk</a> when mastitis is present.
</p>.<p>
Mastitis is usually the result of a bacterial infection. The bacteria typically enter the breast tissue through a cracked nipple that had developed during breastfeeding. 
Whether skipping breastfeeding or pumping, allowing milk to become trapped in the breast (engorgement) can increase the risk of mastitis.
</p>.<p class="credits">REFERENCES:<br><br>

